# Architecture Mode — Layering & Boundaries

Where code belongs, and how layers connect. This complements `code_quality.mdc`
(which covers SRP, composition, anemic models) by defining the **layer boundaries**
those classes live in. Concrete rules, not preferences.

## Layers (dependencies point inward only)
- **Boundary** — API handler, queue consumer, CLI parser, pipeline entry. Validates and
  parses input, calls one service, maps the result/exception outward. No business logic.
- **Service / orchestration** — business logic. Framework-agnostic, depends only on injected
  adapters. Knows nothing about HTTP request/response objects or queue framing.
- **IO / adapter** — DB, external APIs, filesystem. The only layer that performs IO.

A boundary must not run queries; a service must not build an HTTP response. If a piece of
code forces logic into the wrong layer, that is a design smell — stop and use planning mode.

## Boundary Rules
- Validate/sanitize all external input here, before it reaches a service (OWASP — see `team-rules/security.mdc`).
- Use `HTTPStatus`, never bare ints, when mapping outward.
- **MUST NOT** leak stack traces, internal exception text, or paths to the caller — translate to a
  generic outward message; log the detail internally (see `team-rules/conventions.mdc` Logging).

## Errors as a Contract
- Services raise **named domain exceptions** from a dedicated `exceptions.py`
  (subclass `Exception`) — never return a value that silently signals failure.
- Translate domain exceptions to transport errors (HTTP status / queue nack) **only at the boundary**.
- Callers depend on the exception **type**, never on its message string.
- When re-raising across a layer, chain: `raise BoundaryError("...") from domain_error`.

## External Systems
- Wrap every third-party API / provider behind a typed adapter interface.
- Orchestration depends on that interface — **never** imports the SDK directly. Swapping a
  provider then changes one adapter, not the business logic.
- Inject adapters (constructor / DI). **MUST NOT** use module-level globals for mutable shared
  state (see `team-rules/rules.mdc`).

## Pipeline Boundaries (sanitization / transformation flows)
- Each stage has **one responsibility**; stages communicate via typed payloads
  (Pydantic / shared data-model package — see `team-rules/rules.mdc`), not raw dicts.
- Respect **clean vs dirty** zone assumptions when a stage crosses a trust level, and the
  **non-executing storage** flow: do not persist untrusted input in its original form when the
  design requires transformation or isolation first (see `team-rules/security.mdc`).
- Protect path traversal on every read/write/execute at a stage boundary.

## State & Idempotency
- Make retryable operations idempotent (idempotency key or natural upsert) so a re-run is safe.
- A function either returns a value or changes state, not both (Command/Query — see `code_quality.mdc`).

## When Adding a Feature
1. Decide which layer each piece belongs in **before** writing code.
2. Reuse existing services/adapters — do not duplicate IO in a boundary.
3. Keep cross-component/package APIs backward-compatible unless the task requires otherwise (`team-rules/rules.mdc`).

## Tests
- Services are unit-testable in isolation: mock the injected adapters with `unittest.mock`
  (see `test_writing.mdc`). If a service is hard to test without real IO, the boundary is wrong.
